I don't see a need to keep the legacy package. The other changes are so extensive, and you are keeping the legacy package [basically for this function](https://github.com/frictionlessdata/tableschema-py/blob/null-types-constraints-v1/tableschema/infer.py#L151), and a couple of lines [in this method](https://github.com/frictionlessdata/tableschema-py/blob/null-types-constraints-v1/tableschema/infer.py#L104). 

This does not mean you need to rewrite the inference engine in this pull request. Issue #105 is clearly designated for that. However, considering the scope of other changes in this PR, Just updating those lines of code to work with Fields would allow you to remove this newly created legacy package.

@Bianca-T The reason you do not see any AD reads is that this variant is only called with samtools (MIP combines 3 callers: GATK, Freebayes and Samtools). Samtools uses another annotation DP4 to record the same information as the AD field. However, Scout does not read the DP4 field and hence will show AD=0,0 (we will have to think about the best way to fix that). Your variant has 9 high-quality non-reference bases (out of DP=54). 

@Bianca-T An aggregated genotype quality is calculated for all members and scored in the ranking model. An aggregated GT below 20 will add -5 to the rank score. 

@29vd Regarding family 15055. This is a multiallelic call C --> CG,CA that gets splitted. The C --> CG variant is very common and is filtered uppstream of Scout. There is very poor evidence for the C --> CA variant and it is only picked up by GATK, but with no solid support, hence AD=0,0 and "GT=./.". I am suprised GATK recorded it as a variant and it is very likely a false positive.

> The other possibility would be to make a request to given ip/port and see if we get a reply. 

This ought to work. It should identify itself as a tornado server in the headers, at least. We do have something tricky in this particular case because there are *two* leftover runtime files, each claiming to be on the same http endpoint (unsurprising, since it's the default). That's probably pretty common, come to think of it.

@eseiver I think you're exactly right that a runtime file was leftover after a server stopped, for whatever reason. Removing it by hand is an AOK workaround while we figure out why the file was leftover and how we can do better cleaning up after this event occurs. In general, the runtime directory should be safe to delete in its entirety if no Jupyter processes are running.

@PeterHamilton 
Question about links: How do you see the management of links for CryptoObjects?

afais:
- cert <-> public-key <-> private-key links has to be set by server, without client participation;
- it's simple for generated key pair: having the IDs of both parts server sets the mutual links;
- it's relatively simple when importing certificate for the key already in repo: public key is searched for with the blob extracted from certificate;
- it's not simple when importing key pair for a certificate already existing in repo: parse all certificate and look for corresponding public key ??
- the same if building with the links the certificates chain, when importing certificates in random order...

What do you think about introducing of 'key-identifier' column for CryptographicObjects (here is talking my PKCS#11 background) ? -- with that it should be more simple to manage the links.

